{
  "doc_id": "23840",
  "text": "Many DNA tumor viruses inactivate pRB and p21 and derepress expression of the E2F transcription factor family and for HMCV this is important for ATM-driven viral replication [CITATION_1] . Furthermore, deregulation of E2F1 by E7 induces the expression of Chk2 [CITATION_2] , implying that this function of E7 could promote HPV replication. E7 deregulation of E2F, and subsequent nucleotide deficiency, further promotes replication stress and genomic instability [CITATION_3] . In addition, E7 can promote mitotic entry in the presence of a DDR response by accelerating the degradation of the Chk1 binding protein, claspin [CITATION_4] . Therefore, HPVs integrate DNA damage signaling with anti-apoptotic and proliferative functions to create a unique cellular environment that supports viral replication.",
